20:34.984 --> 20:38.196
and you went for it and
the legato was a little bit off.

20:38.237 --> 20:39.906
You know, it didn't sink in.

20:39.948 --> 20:41.491
-Right, okay.

20:41.532 --> 20:43.326
It was a little bit like,
ah, almost there,

20:43.368 --> 20:46.204
but then the problem is
that the fermata,

20:46.245 --> 20:48.206
there was something, that it was
a little bit too short.

20:48.247 --> 20:51.209
So the trumpets, for example,
came in a little bit too late

20:51.250 --> 20:54.420
-and then the oboe, it came in
a little bit too loud. -Yeah.

20:54.462 --> 20:56.214
-And it was...
-Wait, so that's...

20:56.255 --> 20:59.175
-that's the first 20 bars.
-Yes. Yes, yes, yes, yes.

20:59.217 --> 21:01.386
Yes, when the flutes,
for example, they come in,

21:01.427 --> 21:03.471
you didn't really show them
how to phrase,

21:03.513 --> 21:04.764
so they didn't know
where to breathe

21:04.806 --> 21:05.765
and that's the problem,
you know?

21:05.807 --> 21:07.016
It happened with
all the winds...

21:07.058 --> 21:08.935
You know, it wasn't
orange or white,

21:08.977 --> 21:11.396
it was just like something there
in the middle...

21:11.437 --> 21:12.814
You know this thing we've
been talking about, you know,

21:12.855 --> 21:14.732
like, not underlining
everything.

21:14.774 --> 21:17.318
These guys, they know
what they're doing, you know?

21:17.360 --> 21:18.945
But just let it play, you know?

21:18.987 --> 21:20.363
Like, listen to them...
I don't know, but next time,

21:20.405 --> 21:22.031
you have to get it
really perfect, Hai Lai,

21:22.073 --> 21:23.700
really, really perfect.

21:38.131 --> 21:39.757
GLORIA:
Oh, Hesby!

21:39.799 --> 21:43.261
How wonderful to hear from you.

21:43.302 --> 21:46.222
Wha... could you just
repeat that?

21:46.264 --> 21:49.517
I-I... the reception here
isn't...

21:49.559 --> 21:52.603
What
When?

21:52.645 --> 21:55.064
What in the name of Mozart

21:55.106 --> 21:57.275
and motorcycles
and everything else

21:57.316 --> 21:59.318
in the damn world
is wrong with you?!

21:59.360 --> 22:01.154
Hello, darling.

22:01.195 --> 22:03.698
What the hell happened
in your childhood

22:03.740 --> 22:05.908
!
-What, darling,

22:05.950 --> 22:07.702
are you talking about?

22:07.744 --> 22:09.370
Still play dumb?

22:09.412 --> 22:11.247
You stay out of this.

22:11.289 --> 22:12.415
I just spoke to Hesby.

22:12.457 --> 22:14.250
He said you met with him

22:14.292 --> 22:16.544
and now he can't decide
who should perform the Asyla.

22:16.586 --> 22:18.796
He said that we should sort
it out amongst ourselves.

22:20.339 --> 22:23.301
How dare you go sneaking around
behind my back?

22:23.342 --> 22:26.054
Me?! Oh, that's the pot
calling the kettle black.

22:26.095 --> 22:27.638
-Oh, please.

22:27.680 --> 22:29.307
You think I'm stupid?

22:29.348 --> 22:33.019
I mean, all the gifts,
the flowers, the love letters.

22:33.061 --> 22:34.854
I mean, all right,
if you're having an affair,

22:34.896 --> 22:38.107
why don't you just say so?

22:38.149 --> 22:41.152
After all, I might want
to step out myself sometime.

22:41.194 --> 22:45.490
I mean, heaven knows monogamy
was never one of my things.

22:45.531 --> 22:46.699
Those aren't love letters.

22:46.741 --> 22:48.242
They're from Daniel Mahajan.

22:48.284 --> 22:50.495
He wants me to come
and run the Guggenheim.

22:50.536 --> 22:53.289
What? Mah... Mah...

22:53.331 --> 22:57.168
that's ridic... you...

22:57.210 --> 22:59.754
Well, why didn't you tell me?

22:59.796 --> 23:02.507
Because, Thomas, I love you,

23:02.548 --> 23:04.550
but you have
a big fucking mouth!

23:04.592 --> 23:08.179
-No.

23:08.221 --> 23:13.351
No, no, because I am going
to get the piece back

23:13.392 --> 23:18.106
and I am going to crush
your amateur borough orchestra.

23:18.147 --> 23:19.315
Fine!

23:19.357 --> 23:21.025
Well, fine!

23:21.067 --> 23:23.194
No, fine.

